   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import warnings\n",
    "warnings.filterwarnings(\"ignore\", category=DeprecationWarning) \n",
    "warnings.filterwarnings(\"ignore\", category=UserWarning) \n",
    "\n",
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "import pandas as pd\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "from optimizer.constraint import history_penalty\n",
    "from optimizer.loggers import BestTrajectoryLogger\n",
    "from optimizer.plotting import best_trajectory_plot\n",
    "\n",
    "from sklearn.pipeline import Pipeline\n",
    "from optimus_pkg.core.transformers import SelectColumns\n",
    "\n",
    "rng = np.random.RandomState(42)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Historical penalties\n",
    "A walkthrough on how to navigate the trade-off between keeping the solutions close to historical ranges and allowing the optimizer to explore a broader space.\n",
    "\n",
    "## Overview\n",
    "There are cases when pushing the boundaries of the current operational paradigm is the right thing to do, while in other cases we prefer to prioritize getting the buy-in from operators. In this tutorial we'll explore balancing this trade-off in a continuous manner: we'll be able to explicitly say how much we want our optimizer to stick to historical ranges.\n",
    "\n",
    "### What this is\n",
    "- A tutorial on how to balanace historical preferences vs. exploring a broader search space\n",
    "\n",
    "### What this is not\n",
    "- A guide into optimization algorithms and their tuning\n",
    "- A guide into how to properly set-up an optimization problem (penalty tuning, repair functions, etc)\n",
    "- A real world optimizer use case\n",
    "- A guide on how to read diagnostics of an optimization run"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## The historical data and the optimization problem\n",
    "Consider the following 2-dimensional problem in which we want to maximize $x+y$ subject to $(x,y)$ being close to historical values. Each coordinate is also bounded between $-4$ and $4$. This translates to the following problem:\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\begin{align*}\n",
    "\\max \\quad & x + y \\\\\n",
    "\\text{s.t.} \\quad & \\text{(x,y) is close to historical ranges} \\\\\n",
    "& -4 \\leq x,y \\leq 4\n",
    "\\end{align*}\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "The figure below shows historical data, indicating the direction in which the objective function is increasing."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 2,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 432x288 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# Generate fancy shape data\n",
    "n = 10000\n",
    "x = rng.randn(n)\n",
    "y = rng.randn(n)/2\n",
    "X1 = np.c_[x+1.3,y-1]\n",
    "\n",
    "y = -2*np.sin(x) + rng.randn(x.shape[0])/6\n",
    "X2 = np.c_[x,y]\n",
    "\n",
    "X = np.r_[X1, X2]\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.scatter(X[:,0],X[:,1], alpha=.01)\n",
    "plt.ylim(-4,4)\n",
    "plt.xlim(-4,4)\n",
    "plt.ylabel('y');\n",
    "plt.xlabel('x');\n",
    "plt.arrow(2, 2, .5, .5, width=.2)\n",
    "plt.annotate(\"Objective value grows in this direction\", [0.3, 1.5]);\n",
    "plt.plot(2.5, -.6, 'ro')\n",
    "plt.text(2, -1, \"We'd expect OPT to be around here\")\n",
    "plt.title('Historical (x,y) points');"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Using the historical penalty"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The idea is to use an anomaly detection score to penalize solutions that are far from historical regions during the optimization. This will act as any other penalty during the optimization phase. Let's create this penalty and plot the payments we'll incurr in our search space."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 3,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 432x288 with 2 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# We create the penalty by passing the historical values to outlier_penalty\n",
    "p = history_penalty(X)\n",
    "\n",
    "# How this penalty penalizes the regions\n",
    "xx, yy = np.meshgrid(np.linspace(-5, 5, 200), np.linspace(-5, 5, 200))\n",
    "Z = p(np.c_[xx.ravel(), yy.ravel()])\n",
    "Z = Z.reshape(xx.shape)\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.title(\"Penalty payments\");\n",
    "plt.contourf(xx, yy, Z, cmap='Reds');\n",
    "plt.colorbar();"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Let's also make a contour plot of the penalized objective function, that is: objective function - penalties."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 4,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 432x288 with 2 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "mesh_xy = np.c_[xx.ravel(), yy.ravel()]\n",
    "Z = mesh_xy[:,0] + mesh_xy[:,1] - p(mesh_xy)\n",
    "Z = Z.reshape(xx.shape)\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.title(\"f.obj - penalty: The penalty has almost no effect\");\n",
    "plt.contourf(xx, yy, Z, cmap='Blues');\n",
    "plt.colorbar();\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.plot(2.5, -.6, 'ro');"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We **need** to penalize more, since the payment we're currently making in the worst case scenario is only $0.28$, while the objective function can take values up to $8$. That is, the magnitude of our objective function is much bigger. Let's re-fit the penalty with a higher `penalty_multiplier`."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 5,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 432x288 with 2 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# We create the penalty by passing the historical values to outlier_penalty\n",
    "p = history_penalty(X, penalty_multiplier=45)\n",
    "\n",
    "Z = mesh_xy[:,0] + mesh_xy[:,1] - p(mesh_xy)\n",
    "Z = Z.reshape(xx.shape)\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.title(\"f.obj - penalty with a reasonable multiplier\");\n",
    "plt.contourf(xx, yy, Z, cmap='Blues');\n",
    "plt.colorbar();\n",
    "plt.plot(2.5, -.6, 'ro');"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "This makes more sense, we plotted the red dot in where we'd expect to see the optimal value. Let us run the optimization and analyze the solution we get."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 6,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Best solution: [ 2.35640496 -0.41902119]\n",
      "\n",
      "Best objective: 1.9373837700246597\n"
     ]
    },
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 864x504 with 2 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# Set up an optimization problem and check how it behaves\n",
    "from optimizer.solvers import ParticleSwarmSolver\n",
    "\n",
    "sols = []\n",
    "def solve(penalties, plot=False):\n",
    "    bounds = [(-4, 4) for i in range(2)]\n",
    "\n",
    "    solver = ParticleSwarmSolver(\n",
    "        bounds, \n",
    "        sense=\"maximize\", \n",
    "        popsize=15,\n",
    "        maxiter=25,\n",
    "        seed=42, \n",
    "        init='random',\n",
    "        cognitive_parameter=0.05, \n",
    "        inertia=0.2\n",
    "    )\n",
    "\n",
    "    best_trajectory_logger = BestTrajectoryLogger()\n",
    "\n",
    "    while not solver.stop():\n",
    "        parameters = solver.ask()\n",
    "        objective_values = np.sum(parameters, axis=1) - np.sum([p(parameters) for p in penalties], axis=0)\n",
    "        solver.tell(parameters, objective_values)\n",
    "        sols.append(solver.best()[0])\n",
    "        best_trajectory_logger.log(solver)\n",
    "    print(\"Best solution: {}\\n\\nBest objective: {}\".format(*solver.best()))\n",
    "    if plot:\n",
    "        best_trajectory_plot(best_trajectory_logger, penalties, bounds, variable_labels=['x', 'y']);\n",
    "        plt.tight_layout();\n",
    "\n",
    "solve([p])\n",
    "\n",
    "fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(12,7))\n",
    "ret = ax.contourf(xx, yy, p(np.c_[xx.ravel(), yy.ravel()]).reshape(xx.shape), cmap='Reds')\n",
    "fig.colorbar(ret)\n",
    "for i, (sx,sy) in enumerate(sols[1:]):\n",
    "    prevx, prevy = sols[i]\n",
    "    ax.arrow(prevx, prevy, sx-prevx, sy-prevy, width=.02, color='black', alpha=.4)\n",
    "    ax.scatter(prevx, prevy, color='black', s=10)\n",
    "ax.set_ylim(-4,4);\n",
    "ax.set_xlim(-4,4);\n",
    "ax.arrow(0, 0, .5, .5, width=.1)\n",
    "ax.plot([-4,4], [4,-4])\n",
    "_ = ax.annotate(\"Objective value grows in this direction\", [0.3, -.15]);\n",
    "_ = ax.set_title('Optimization trace in black dots, in red the payments we make');"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The black arrows represent the evolution of the best solution provided by the algorithm. We see it converges towards $(2.55, -0.55)$, close to where we thought it would be  this optimization is history guided!"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Validating that history is constraining our solutions\n",
    "In real life we have more dimensions and cannot plot this, but we can use optimization diagnostic tools! Take a look at the optimization diagnostic tutorial, or just take a peak on how the solve function calls `best_trajectory_plot` and uses the `best_trajectory_logger`."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 7,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Best solution: [ 2.35640496 -0.41902119]\n",
      "\n",
      "Best objective: 1.9373837700246597\n"
     ]
    },
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1080x374.4 with 7 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "solve([p], plot=True)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We see here that the `history_penalty` slack is dark blue, that is, there's not much room to move further away from history and not incur a penalty. This means that the historical constraint is limiting us from increasing the objective, $x+y$.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Choosing the multiplier\n",
    "Optimization diagnostic tools can help determine an appropriate penalty multiplier: if the multiplier is very low, the cost of violating the `history_penalty` is so low that the optimizer will just pay and violate it  we can detect this behavior on the diagnostic report. Consider the following diagnostic plot - we've set the penalty multiplier quite low and our optimizer is willingly incurring large penalties as a result."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 8,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Best solution: [4. 4.]\n",
      "\n",
      "Best objective: 7.776461804999271\n"
     ]
    },
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1080x374.4 with 7 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "p = history_penalty(X, penalty_multiplier=1)\n",
    "solve([p], plot=True)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Pandas support\n",
    "We can use a Pandas DataFrame out of the box"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 9,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 432x288 with 2 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "df = pd.DataFrame(X)\n",
    "df.columns = ['x', 'y']\n",
    "df_penalty = history_penalty(df)\n",
    "plt.scatter(x=df['x'], y=df['y'], \n",
    "            c=df_penalty(df), \n",
    "            alpha=.2, cmap='bwr');\n",
    "plt.xlabel('x');\n",
    "plt.ylabel('y');\n",
    "plt.colorbar();\n",
    "plt.title('Paying for anomalies in a DataFrame');"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Pipeline support\n",
    "We might want/need to penalize being far from historical sources on a subset of columns, for example in situations where our predictive model is generating dynamic features/controls. We recommend leveraging `sklearn.pipeline.Pipeline` to achieve this, and if the transformers in the pipeline support `pd.DataFrame`, then we can leverage them to select subset of columns for the penalty function. This is useful, for example, when we have:\n",
    "\n",
    "- a data frame with 60 columns that captures all the operation\n",
    "- we're having trouble getting recommendations buy-in in some specific area of the operation (say, cyclones)\n",
    "- we can penalize only on the columns related to cyclones, which might have only 5 columns\n",
    "\n",
    "In the following example we select column $y$ for detecting historical deviations only in that dimension"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 10,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 432x288 with 2 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "df = pd.DataFrame(X)\n",
    "df.columns = ['x', 'y']\n",
    "\n",
    "pipe = Pipeline([('x_select', SelectColumns(['y']))])\n",
    "pipe.fit(df) # Pipeline has to be fit\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "df_penalty = history_penalty(df, pipeline=pipe)\n",
    "plt.scatter(x=df['x'], y=df['y'], \n",
    "            c=df_penalty(df), \n",
    "            alpha=.2, cmap='bwr');\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.xlabel('x');\n",
    "plt.ylabel('y');\n",
    "plt.title('Paying only for anomalies in y');\n",
    "plt.colorbar();"
   ]
  }
 ],
